			<h4><a id="comment_link_64267646" name="comment_link_64267646" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23237496&amp;cid=64267646" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64267646)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64267646" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64267646); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~smoot123">smoot123</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~smoot123">( 1027084 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64267646"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64267646"><p><div class="quote"><p>It's long past time that companies can be allowed to just dump new tech out there without sufficient testing to ensure it is safe, reliable and does what it is intended to do without any unexpected side effects. The same way we regulate drugs.</p></div><p>At the risk of going off topic, nothing is absolutely safe. There are always tradeoffs between time-to-market, safety, cost, and functionality. I can make a perfectly secure car but it'll be powered off, encased in lead, and launched towards Alpha Centuri at near the speed of light.</p><p>Given the glacial pace new drugs get released, I'm pretty sure we don't want to regulate car keys the same way we regulate drugs. Do you really want it to take 10 years to update the OTA protocols between a car and a fob? Do you<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

